# Taipan — The AI-Native Programming Language

[![Python 3.10+](https://img.shields.io/badge/python-3.10+-blue.svg)](https://www.python.org/downloads/)
[![License: MIT](https://img.shields.io/badge/License-MIT-yellow.svg)](https://opensource.org/licenses/MIT)
[![Tests](https://img.shields.io/badge/tests-151%20passing-brightgreen.svg)]()
[![Code style](https://img.shields.io/badge/code%20style-taipan-000000.svg)]()

> **Taipan** is a modern, expressive programming language designed from the ground up with AI-native features. It combines the simplicity of Python, the safety of Rust, and the power of AI-assisted development.

## Quick Start

```bash
# Install Taipan
pip install taipan

# Run a Taipan program
tai run hello_world.pk

# Interactive REPL
tai repl

# Initialize a new project
tai init my_project
cd my_project
tai test
```

```pk
// hello_world.pk
func greet(name: String) -> String {
    return f"Hello, {name}!"
}

show(greet("Taipan"))
```

## Features

### 🧠 AI-Native
- **AI-powered error explanations** — `TAIPAN_AI_ERRORS=1` enables AI suggestions on every error
- **Local LLM support** — Works with Ollama (free, private, offline) via `ai.ask()`, `ai.summarize()`, `ai.generateCode()`
- **Built-in AI assistant** — `ai myBot` declarations for AI-augmented coding

### 🏗 Modern Syntax
- **Type hints** — `func add(a: Int, b: Int) -> Int`
- **F-strings** — `f"Hello, {name}!"`
- **Pattern matching** — `match value { case Ok(v) => ... }`
- **First-class functions** — Closures, lambdas, higher-order functions
- **Classes with inheritance** — Full OOP with `extends`, `super`, `self`

### ⚡ Performance
- **Tree-walk interpreter** — For development and debugging
- **Bytecode VM** — `--vm` flag for optimized execution
- **C transpiler** — Compile to native C for maximum speed

### 🔧 Developer Experience
- **VS Code extension** — Syntax highlighting, diagnostics, autocomplete, hover docs, go-to-definition, symbol outline
- **LSP server** — Full Language Server Protocol support
- **Package manager** — `peek` for publishing and installing packages
- **Built-in test framework** — `test "name" { assert(...) }` syntax
- **Professional error messages** — Rust-style errors with source context and underlines

## Installation

### From PyPI (when published)
```bash
pip install taipan
```

### From Source
```bash
git clone https://github.com/peeyush/taipan.git
cd taipan
pip install -e ".[dev]"
```

### VS Code Extension
1. Copy `vscode_extension/` to `~/.vscode/extensions/taipan-2.1.0/`
2. Run `npm install` in the extension directory
3. Reload VS Code

## Usage

### CLI Commands

| Command | Description | Example |
|---------|-------------|---------|
| `tai run <file.tp>` | Run a Taipan program | `tai run hello.pk` |
| `tai run --vm <file>` | Run with VM backend | `tai run --vm fib.pk` |
| `tai test <file>` | Run test blocks | `tai test tests.pk` |
| `tai repl` | Interactive REPL | — |
| `tai check <file>` | Lint without running | `tai check program.pk` |
| `tai format <file>` | Auto-format code | `tai format messy.pk` |
| `tai init [name]` | Initialize project | `tai init myapp` |
| `tai build` | Verify package | — |
| `tai tokens <file>` | Debug: show tokens | — |
| `tai ast <file>` | Debug: show AST | — |

### Package Manager (`peek`)

```bash
peek init                    # Initialize package
peek install <pkg>[@v]       # Install package
peek uninstall <pkg>         # Remove package
peek list                    # List all packages
peek search <query>          # Search registry
peek info <pkg>              # Show package info
peek publish                 # Publish to registry
peek update                  # Update all packages
peek build                   # Verify package
```

### Python Interop

```pk
import python "numpy" as np
import python "pandas" as pd

let arr = np.array([1, 2, 3])
show(arr.mean())
```

## Language Tour

### Variables & Types
```pk
let name = "Taipan"      // Mutable
const PI = 3.14159        // Immutable

// Type hints
let count: Int = 42
let price: Float = 9.99
let items: List = [1, 2, 3]
```

### Functions
```pk
func add(a: Int, b: Int) -> Int {
    return a + b
}

// Default parameters
func greet(name: String, greeting: String = "Hello") -> String {
    return f"{greeting}, {name}!"
}

// Higher-order functions
func map(list: List, fn: Func) -> List {
    let result = []
    for item in list {
        result.append(fn(item))
    }
    return result
}
```

### Classes
```pk
class Animal {
    func init(name: String) {
        self.name = name
    }
    func speak() -> String {
        return "..."
    }
}

class Dog extends Animal {
    func speak() -> String {
        return f"{self.name} says Woof!"
    }
}

let dog = new Dog("Buddy")
show(dog.speak())
```

### Concurrency
```pk
func worker(id: Int) {
    show(f"Worker {id} starting")
    time.sleep(0.5)
    show(f"Worker {id} done")
}

// Spawn concurrent tasks
for i in 1..5 {
    spawn worker(i)
}
wait
show("All workers finished!")
```

### AI Features
```pk
// Built-in AI assistant
ai myBot
show(myBot.ask("What is a closure?"))
show(myBot.summarize("Long text here..."))

// Or use the AI module directly
import ai
show(ai.isAvailable())           // Check if AI is available
show(ai.generateCode("fibonacci")) // Generate code
```

### Error Handling
```pk
try {
    let result = 10 / 0
} catch (err) {
    show(f"Caught error: {err}")
}

// Or use catch expression
let safe_result = catch { 10 / 0 }
if safe_result != null {
    show(f"Error: {safe_result}")
}
```

### Testing
```pk
func factorial(n: Int) -> Int {
    if n <= 1 { return 1 }
    return n * factorial(n - 1)
}

test "factorial of 0 is 1" {
    assert(factorial(0) == 1)
}

test "factorial of 5 is 120" {
    assert(factorial(5) == 120)
}

test "factorial handles negatives" {
    let err = catch { factorial(-1) }
    assert(err != null)
}
```

## Standard Library

| Module | Functions |
|--------|-----------|
| `math` | `sqrt`, `pow`, `sin`, `cos`, `log`, `random`, `randint`, `factorial`, `gcd`, `clamp`, `lerp`, `pi`, `e` |
| `string` | `upper`, `lower`, `split`, `join`, `replace`, `strip`, `startsWith`, `endsWith`, `contains`, `substring`, `regexMatch` |
| `json` | `stringify`, `parse`, `save`, `load` |
| `time` | `now`, `timestamp`, `sleep`, `year`, `month`, `day`, `hour`, `minute`, `second` |
| `file` | `read`, `write`, `append`, `lines`, `delete`, `exists`, `listDir`, `mkdir` |
| `collections` | `stack`, `queue`, `deque`, `priority_queue`, `heap`, `graph`, `binary_tree` |
| `network` | `get`, `post`, `put`, `delete`, `head`, `patch` |
| `ai` | `ask`, `summarize`, `generateCode`, `classify`, `translate`, `sentiment`, `isAvailable` |

## Configuration

Create `taipan.toml` in your project root:

```toml
[package]
name = "my-project"
version = "0.1.0"
description = "My Taipan project"
author = "Your Name"
license = "MIT"

[dependencies]
# other_pkg = "1.0.0"
```

## Environment Variables

| Variable | Description |
|----------|-------------|
| `TAIPAN_AI_ERRORS` | Enable AI-powered error explanations |
| `OPENAI_API_KEY` | OpenAI API key for cloud AI features |
| `OLLAMA_HOST` | Ollama server URL (default: `http://localhost:11434`) |
| `TAIPAN_DEBUG` | Show full Python tracebacks |

